description.text:
Designed to celebrate May the 4th be with you Day!!!

Be your own Death Star architect! Create your own Death Star patterns with the Star Wars Death Star Slide Puzzle.

Remixed from roy ang's Death Star tiles, https://www.myminifactory.com/object/scifi-diorama-tiles-1-72-scale-29722. (edit 9/8/17 appears to be gone, try https://www.myminifactory.com/users/IzzyMel) that I am thinking he was inspired by Tom Spina's awesome designs for a home theater: http://gizmodo.com/turn-any-wall-into-a-death-star-with-these-mix-and-matc-1465236444 .

I loved the idea of star wars tiles, but wanted a way to print a bunch and keep them contained so that I could move them around for different patterns, kinda like a big fidget. I used ClassyGoat's slide puzzle template. http://www.thingiverse.com/ClassyGoat/about and lined up the tiles as best I could.

I added a "solution" image for those who want a solution, based roughly on the number of objects/shape of what is on the tile. Ideally someone will make a star wars puzzle that will have a really nice elegant solution of matching tiles.
I will probably end up gluing the bottom and top together instead of the nut and bolt solution, but wanted to tweak it before doing that.

description.text:
My friend needed an armature that his camera sight could latch onto. So I designed an armature for him. 
But to make it really unique, I added the architectural styling found in Deus Ex Human Revolution. So when anyone sees this, they know it was custom and 3d-printed! 
The most interesting result into this experiment, was that the trussed part appeared to perform better in Solidworks stress simulations, as compared to a part made from bulk material.
This explains why a lot of buildings these days are built with these organic-looking trusses, since you can actually tweak the macro-structure to support loads more effectively with less material.

Print with the design facing upwards. You may need to modify the file to fit your camera sight. Just to be sure, I have included the original solidworks file. The discs at the bottom are to prevent warping and can be removed after printing. Print without raft :)
The trusses are 1.6mm thick thereabouts, print with thin-walled profile if you have one, and set the first layer thicker so that warping is reduced.
Also if you're using an Ultimaker with Cura, print the inside first, before printing the outer skin. As the trusses cool, they will poke into the outer skin, if you print them after the skin.
I printed my part in PLA, which has a low glass transition temperature of about 58C. So my friend will be seeing if it holds up to use outdoors - haha! I'll probably do a print in ABS for him if it gets funky.

2- Metal gear standard size servos ( https://www.banggood.com/JX-PDI-6221MG-20KG-Large-Torque-Digital-Coreless-Servo-For-RC-Model-p-973947.html?rmmds=myorder)
2- 5k 10 turn Potentiometers (https://www.banggood.com/3590S-2-502L-5K-Ohm-Rotary-Precision-Multi-Turn-Potentiometer-p-1010809.html?rmmds=myorder
1- 30206 tapered roller bearing (https://www.banggood.com/30202-30206-Steel-Single-Row-Taper-Tapered-Roller-Bearing-Metric-Taper-Bearings-p-1096085.html?rmmds=myorder)
1 or 2 (or in my case 3) carbon fiber plates 200x300x2mm (https://www.banggood.com/3K-2003002mm-Plain-Weave-Carbon-Fiber-Plate-Panel-Sheet-p-1085797.html?rmmds=myorder
8mm carbon fiber tube ( https://www.banggood.com/2Pcs-8mm6mm500mm-3k-Carbon-Fiber-Tube-Black-Carbon-Pipe-p-1101658.html?rmmds=myorder)
1-KFL006 pillow block bearing (pillow block removed, https://www.banggood.com/20253035mm-Inner-Diameter-Flange-Bearing-Zinc-Alloy-KFL004567-Flange-Pillow-Block-Bearings-p-1055268.html?rmmds=myorder)
2-8mm shaft collars
2-8mm (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B002BBODZY/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1)
2-Robot Biaxial Servo Spare Part Round Servo 25T (https://www.banggood.com/Robot-Biaxial-Servo-Spare-Part-Round-Servo-25T-Mount-Bracket-for-DIY-Robot-p-1068917.html)
2- 6001 bearings 8mm id (https://www.banggood.com/Deep-Groove-Ball-Bearings-6000-60052RS-High-Speed-Bearing-Steel-p-942862.html
Various M3 Screws and nuts and washers,
most of the holes sized for M3 or 6/32 screws, I used m3 for almost all screws and nuts

You need to dissemble the servos and solder in onto the wires that run the internal pot and rewire them to the external pot. I drilled a hole in the aluminum servo side to run the wires out, I hot glued the wires in place inside the servo, kind of like a strain relief.
You have to cut the pillow block part off the pillow block bearing. I wanted the set screws on the shaft of the big base gear, but not the added wight and bulk of the pillow block.
the hole in the bottom base is for a 1/4-20 blind nut so that this can sit on a tripod if i want to. I ordered 3 of the carbon fiber plates, one is going to get bolted to the bottom of the lower base plate for added strength, and 2 for the main pan tilt plate, so that i can double side it, one side for antennas and the other for a diversity receiver.
The horizontal holes on the bottom base plate are for a small fan, to cool the 5.8GHZ repeater VTX.
I printed everything in Hatchbox black ABS, most of the prints are 40 or 50% infill with everything printed at 101% to accommodate ABS shrink
The vertical and horizontal tubes are 10mm OD (6mm ID) Carbon fiber square tubes from Ebay
I'm sure I'm missing something in this description, if you have questions please ask me.

This thing is big, I built it to handle 2 antennas, a IBCrazy 2.4Ghz cross-hair and a homemade 2.4 Ghz Helical. The plan is to add a third antenna to the array, off on the side, which will be a 2.4 Ghz Mad Mushroom or a Skew Planer. I have 2 ImmersionRC 2.4GHz receivers, a single receiver and a diversity receiver, one will run both of the antennas on the tracker, and 1 will be for the skew planer mounded to the side of the tracker.

Pente Grammai (five lines) Designed for the visually impaired to be able to play.

Recently at a game night, I was introduced to this awesome and simple game: Pente Grammai (five lines). I also met someone new at the event, who was blind. So playing was a bit of a challenge on the playing field we were using. This inspired me to create this visually impaired friendly version. They will be able to feel and identify the different pieces easily, and where everything is on the playing board without worry of moving pieces accidently. I also made the dice larger and with easy to feel dimples.

I have included a single file with everything to print at once... as well as each individual component.

History of the Game:
“Five Lines is one of the oldest board games known, coming from Ancient Greece where it was known as Pente Grammai. Around 600 BC the Greek poet Alkaios referred to the game in one of his poems; and gaming tables in terracotta with the typical five parallel lines have been found in graves dating to the same period. During the decades around 500 BC the Athenians imagined Ajax and Achilles playing the game during the siege of Troy. Five Lines, or 'the game of the heroes', was regarded as a noble game for centuries and was very popular; as it was during Roman Imperial times, when a number of descriptions of the game occur in contemporary literature, and boards with rectangular grids can be found scratched into pavements in Roman towns.”

Game Play:

  • Each player places five game pieces on opposing sides of the board, one at the end of each line.
  • The central line is known as "the sacred line".
  • Game pieces move counter-clockwise alternately on the roll of a single die.
  • Game piece may land only on a vacant line, or on the sacred line.
  • If there is a legal move, you must move. Even if you are on the sacred line. You may not be able to move at all, so next players turn.
  • The winner is the first to assemble all their game pieces on the sacred line opposite their starting position.

If you're in the SCA - this is a perfect game to play at Pennsic War while drinking your mead ;)

description.text:
Introducing the first beta test of our OpenTactics project! Somewhere between a boardgame and a miniature wargame, OpenTactics uses the core dice system from our Pocket-Tactics games and blows up the action with modular terrain scale to the characters. We want the game to be expansive and grant players the ability to create their own characters and share them with the community, gathering all content together in a shared online library here on Thingiverse and on our own site.

INSTRUCTIONS- For our first test, we're pitting a viking war party against the detachment from a horde of human/troll hybrids. To play this scenario, you'll want to print some combination of at least 9 tiles (or more, if you feel like using a larger map), making a river in the center from the water tiles. Print at least one catwalk and place it in the center as a bridge. Set up the map and choose opposite sides for deployment, treating the bridge as an objective.

You'll want to print the following models: PLAYER ONE (Viking Freeman x2, Viking Raider x2, Viking Guard x2, Jarl's Champion x1, Vala x1), PLAYER TWO (Trollspawn Brute x2, Trollspawn Lobber x2, Trollspawn Warrior x2, Trollspawn Wolfrider x1, Runescarred x1).

title: GarageMote case, chain-drive magnet mount, and sensor pylon

description.text:
This is a crude case and chain adapter for LowPowerLab's GarageMote:

https://lowpowerlab.com/guide/garagemote/

The case provides full access to all the necessary ports and connections and the light from the LED is visible through the case, depending on the material/color used. The case does not snap or screw together, the intention is to glue it together with a small bit of super glue on the corners. A bit of filing/sanding may be necessary to get a nice tight fit and open up the programming port. The GarageMote I/O board is a tight fight on my printer, a bit of filing on the edge of the PCB can make it easier to install.

The chain adapter is for garage door openers using a chain drive, obviously. The magnet provides quite a bit of adhesion to the chain on its own, this adapter keeps it in place and the fingers are intended to snap around the roller to provide an additional mechanical attachment. Depending on your chain, the fingers may not fit in the narrower gap between the inner plates, they only fit between the outer plates for me, so it can only attach to every other link.

Please note, at the time of posting, I have not yet deployed these prints, so I cannot vouch for the longevity of this solution, any magnets falling from the chain are at your own risk.

UPDATE (2017-04-27): Added additional chain bracket w/ shorter fingers for slightly slimmer chains.

UPDATE (2017-04-30): Added sensor pylon and completed project. Pro tip, when you glue the case together, put a dab of hot glue on the antenna, it sucks to crack it open to reattach if it breaks. Note that the pylon is half filled towards the top to keep the sensor against the closer edge. Shine light through to adjust the sensor height to the center of the magnet. Double sided tape on the base holds the pylon in place and holds the sensor at the preset height. I spliced into the control wire and used wire nuts to hold them together, this was easier than trying to feed two wires into the opener. Aluminum tape keeps the sensor wires securely away from the chain and everything else is held in place with zip ties. GarageMote works great on my Craftsman opener!

This is a piece I built to support the Y idler pulley on my Makerbot.
As shipped, the Y idler on the Makerbot is just a plastic pulley on a bolt screwed into the baseplate.  This is really not a good design.  The baseplate can flex, which makes it hard to properly adjust the belt tension.  The pully is bare plastic turning on a fixed metal axle, without even a bushing, and can after a while get very noisy.
This modification adds a bracing arm which attaches around the end of one of the Y rails, using the same hex nuts that hold the Y rail end cap on.  You will have to use longer screws to account for the thickness of this piece.  Two bearings are pressed into the piece, and these now support the 4mm bolt that the pulley turns with.  This makes the Y stage much quieter and smoother, and makes it easier to properly adjust the Y belt tension.
Warning - this is an experimental piece and may require some trimming to fit properly, some of the clearances are really tight.  This is uploaded for reference purposes only.

Print out the part.  Trim as needed.
Take two ball bearings (13mm OD, 4mm ID, 5mm thick) and press them into the pockets in the piece.
Remove the 4mm bolt which holds the Y belt idler pulley in palce.  You might have to trim the pulley or the part slightly to make it fit.  You also need to keep the belt looped around the pulley as you do this as there's no way to install the belt afterwards.
Insert the 4mm bolt through the bearings and pulley, and use a single 4mm hex nut to lock the bolt, bearings, and idler pulley together.
Remove the end cap from the right-side Y axis rod on your Makerbot.  Slide the rod out.  Put the idler support where the end of the rod goes into the frame on the Makerbot.  The bottom of the 4mm bolt that secures the idler pully will stick through the hole in the baseplate, but should be able to turn freely.
Slide the Y axis rod back in, and then attach the rod end cap with four 3mm nuts and screws.
Re-adjust the belt tension and reconnect anything else you disconnected.  Your Y axis should now be quieter and smoother.

2 x M2x20mm or M2x16mm (attach bucket to arm)
2 x M3x20mm or M3x16mm (attach bearing pins to arm)

Use 2 M2x20mm or M2x16mm screws to secure the bucket to the end of the catapult arm. Make sure the rubber-band notches on the other end of the arm are facing up.

I used a hair dryer to soften the supports while inserting the bearings, then I super-glued the supports into the slots on the base. Press bearing pins through the bearings, and use M2x16mm or M2x20mm screws to secure the catapult arm to the bearing pins.

Press-fit an M3x8mm hex-socket screw into the stop-bar thumbscrew. Use a screw driver or allen wrench to thread the screw into the stop-bar the first time, then the thumbscrew shouldn't slip.
